If you are using Java 7 or earlier you can refer to this [post][1].

If you are using Java 8 you could do:

        DateTimeFormatter timeFormatter = DateTimeFormatter.ISO_DATE_TIME;
        TemporalAccessor accessor = timeFormatter.parse(&quot;2015-10-27T16:22:27.605-07:00&quot;);
    
        Date date = Date.from(Instant.from(accessor));
        System.out.println(date);

Update
------
As pointed out by @BasilBourque in the comment, [TemporalAccessor][2] is java framework level interface, and is not advisable to use in the application code and it is advisable to use concrete classes rather than the interfaces.

&gt; This interface is a framework-level interface that should not be widely used in application code. Instead, applications should create and pass around instances of concrete types, such as LocalDate. There are many reasons for this, part of which is that implementations of this interface may be in calendar systems other than ISO. See ChronoLocalDate for a fuller discussion of the issues.

There a few concrete classes available to use, like [LocalDate][3], [LocalDateTime][4], [OffsetDateTime][5], [ZonedDateTime][6] and etc..

    DateTimeFormatter timeFormatter = DateTimeFormatter.ISO_DATE_TIME;

	OffsetDateTime offsetDateTime = OffsetDateTime.parse(&quot;2015-10-27T16:22:27.605-07:00&quot;, timeFormatter);

	Date date = Date.from(Instant.from(offsetDateTime));
	System.out.println(date);


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2201925/converting-iso-8601-compliant-string-to-java-util-date
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/temporal/TemporalAccessor.html
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDate.html
  [4]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDateTime.html
  [5]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/OffsetDateTime.html
  [6]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/ZonedDateTime.html

