With Java 9 you can use [`Optional.or()`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api//java.base/java/util/Optional.html#or(java.util.function.Supplier)) instead. It expects a *supplier* of *optional* as an argument and returns an *optional* object.

Method `or()` would be triggered only if it was invoked on an empty optional. And you can apply `or()` in the chain as many times as you need, providing one alternative after another.

If we imagine that *optional* is a *box*, then `or()` checks whether the *box* is empty and if it is the case it delivers another *box*.

`orElseGet()` is different, it doesn&#39;t give you a *box*, instead it hands you the *contents* as is. For that reason, it expects a *supplier* of type `T` (not a supplier of optional). And you can&#39;t invoke methods defined in the optional class after applying `orElseGet()` - the *box* is gone, now there&#39;s an object of type `T`.

That&#39;s how it would look like with `Optional.or()`:


    public Optional&lt;BigDecimal&gt; getBillAmount(final String id) {
        
        return getBookAccount(id)
            .map(bookAccount -&gt; {
                // do something and return BigDecimal
                return someBalance.get().setScale(2, RoundingMode.HALF_UP);
            })
            .or(() -&gt; {
                /*perform multiple actions related to the functional logic and then return a BigDecimal*/
                return someOptionalBigDecimal;
            });
    }

With Java 8 there&#39;s no possibility to build a similar method chain. I would probably do it like this:

    public Optional&lt;BigDecimal&gt; getBillAmount(final String id) {
        
